Project Journey

1. Discovery Call

Initial conversation with founders to understand their vision and current workflow. During the call, I sketched out their existing process in real-time to ensure we were aligned on the current state.

Key Outcomes:
  • Mapped current therapy booking and management workflow
  • Identified key pain points in their manual process
  • Established trust through visual collaboration
Real-time sketch created during discovery call showing current workflow

2. Founder Questionnaire

Sent a structured questionnaire to the founders to dive deeper into their business goals, technical constraints, and vision for the product. This helped uncover assumptions and priorities.

Key Outcomes:
  • Clarified business model and revenue expectations
  • Identified must-have vs. nice-to-have features
  • Understood technical and resource constraints

3. Mystery Shopping

Went through the entire customer experience from first contact to therapy sessions. I actually took 6 therapy sessions to truly understand the user journey, pain points, and opportunities from a client's perspective.

Key Outcomes:
  • Experienced firsthand the booking and onboarding friction
  • Identified critical touchpoints where clients drop off
  • Documented the entire journey with real data and insights
Complete user journey from first contact through 6 therapy sessions

4. Collaborative Process Mapping

Expanded on the original sketch in a FigJam board where founders could add their input. Green stickies for what they loved, red stickies for what needed attention. This created a shared understanding of priorities.

Key Outcomes:
  • Visual alignment on current vs. desired state
  • Identified 12 critical pain points to address
  • Built consensus on where to focus first
Collaborative FigJam session with founder feedback

5. Business Model Canvas

Created a comprehensive Business Model Canvas to ensure the product strategy aligned with their business goals. This helped validate assumptions about customer segments, value propositions, and revenue streams.

Key Outcomes:
  • Validated core value proposition
  • Identified key partnerships needed
  • Clarified customer acquisition strategy
Business Model Canvas defining the strategic foundation

6. Customer Personas

Developed detailed personas for therapists, clients, and practice managers to ensure we were building for real user needs, not assumptions.

Key Outcomes:
  • Created 3 primary personas with goals and pain points
  • Identified distinct needs for each user type
  • Prioritized features based on persona impact
Therapist, Client, and Practice Manager personas

7. Right Product Team Exploration

Explored what the ideal product team structure would look like for their startup phase, helping them understand roles, responsibilities, and hiring priorities.

Key Outcomes:
  • Defined product team structure for MVP phase
  • Identified critical roles to hire vs. outsource
  • Created a hiring roadmap aligned with product milestones
Ideal product team structure and hiring roadmap

8. User Journey Mapping

Mapped out detailed user journeys for each persona, from discovery to booking to post-session follow-up. This revealed opportunities for automation and delightful experiences.

Key Outcomes:
  • Created 5+ detailed user journey maps
  • Identified 8 automation opportunities
  • Prioritized features by journey impact
User journey maps showing therapist and client experiences

9. Product Screenshots

The final product delivered on the strategic vision with a clean, intuitive interface that addressed the core pain points identified during discovery.

Key Outcomes:
  • Launched MVP in 6 weeks post-discovery
  • Achieved 85% therapist satisfaction in early testing
  • Reduced booking time from 15 minutes to 2 minutes
Therapist dashboard showing key performance indicators and analytics
Patient management interface with streamlined booking flow
